---
import Base from '../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import '../../../styles/zenagent.css';
---
<Base
  title="ZenAgent — one CNAS token, the whole clinic reports | ZenRIS"
  description="ZenAgent connects the CNAS token and the card reader once, on a single station. The rest of the clinic reports to CNAS from the browser — the system routes automatically. No token shuffling, no legacy desktop app on every computer."
  lang="en"
  altHref="/platforma/zenagent/"
>
  <section class="wrap za-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">ZenAgent · automatic CNAS claims</p>
    <h1>One CNAS token.<br />The whole clinic reports.</h1>
    <p class="lead">The token for CNAS (Romania's national health insurance house) and the card reader sit on one
      station, connected once. From there, every computer in the clinic reports to CNAS straight from the browser —
      <strong>ZenAgent routes each operation to the right station, automatically</strong>. No token carried from
      desk to desk, no SIUI (the legacy desktop reporting app) installed on every machine.</p>
    <div class="za-ctas">
      <a class="btn btn-solid" href="/en/demo/">Book a demo</a>
      <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="#cum">How it works →</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap section" id="cum">
    <div class="flow" aria-hidden="true">
      <div class="node stations">
        <span class="n-tag">RIS stations · browser</span>
        <span class="n-row">Front desk</span>
        <span class="n-row">Physician</span>
        <span class="n-row hot">Billing</span>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow"><span class="a-lbl">request</span></div>
      <div class="node hub">
        <span class="n-title">ZenRIS</span>
        <span class="n-sub">control plane · routing</span>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow"><span class="a-lbl">typed command</span></div>
      <div class="node agent">
        <span class="n-title">ZenAgent station</span>
        <span class="n-sub">CNAS token · card reader</span>
        <span class="n-chip">PIN stays local</span>
      </div>
      <div class="arrow"><span class="a-lbl">reporting</span></div>
      <div class="node cnas">
        <span class="n-title">CNAS</span>
        <span class="n-sub">PIAS</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="flow-cap">The request starts from any station. ZenRIS routes it to the station that holds the eligible
      token. The PIN is entered only there. Nobody moves anything.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap za-grid">
      <div>
        <h2>Centralized in the RIS, not scattered across stations</h2>
        <p>The RIS is the brain. It decides which CNAS operation is needed, for which contract and with which
          certificate, then sends agents typed commands over a secure channel. The local agent holds no authority —
          which tenant, which station and which permissions are all set by the server, from enrollment and identity.</p>
        <p>Every command has a deadline, a correlation ID and is bound to a specific device. Nothing runs on
          trust coming from the station.</p>
      </div>
      <ul class="check-list single">
        <li><strong>Typed commands</strong> — not free-form scripts; every operation has a clear contract.</li>
        <li><strong>Server-derived authority</strong> — the station doesn't declare its own permissions.</li>
        <li><strong>Complete audit</strong> — every CNAS operation is logged: who, what, when.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap za-grid">
      <div>
        <h2>The agent installs once, where the hardware is</h2>
        <p>ZenAgent runs in the background, as a service, on the station that holds the CNAS token and/or the card
          reader. It installs per-machine, starts inert and activates only after enrollment. Updates are signed,
          verified, with automatic rollback if anything is unhealthy.</p>
        <p>The operator never opens or configures an agent application day to day. They work only from the RIS —
          the agent stays invisible until it's needed.</p>
      </div>
      <ul class="check-list single">
        <li><strong>Per-machine install</strong>, inert until the station is enrolled.</li>
        <li><strong>Signed updates</strong>, verified by manifest and hash, with health-gated rollback.</li>
        <li><strong>Zero daily setup</strong> for the operator — everything from the RIS.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">This is the difference</p>
      <h2 class="za-h2c">The token works for the whole clinic — without anyone moving it.</h2>
      <div class="za-grid center">
        <div>
          <p>When a station without a token requests a CNAS operation, the RIS routes it automatically to the station
            that holds the eligible token for that operator, tax ID and contract. Deterministic, with no fallback
            between certificates: if the token is missing, expired or ambiguous, the system stops safely
            (<strong>fail-closed</strong>) — it never guesses.</p>
          <p>The card reader is always local to the station you work from. The token can execute for another station,
            but only through an explicitly authorized route — and the PIN stays on the token's station.</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="check-list single">
          <li><strong>Routing by capability</strong>, not by whoever happens to have the token plugged in.</li>
          <li><strong>Fail-closed</strong> — on any uncertainty it stops, it doesn't invent a signature.</li>
          <li><strong>The clinical flow continues</strong> even if the token or CNAS is momentarily unavailable.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>The keys stay on the token. Always.</h2>
      <p class="lead">ZenRIS never stores P12/PFX certificates, PINs or private keys. Security isn't a promise —
        it's a consequence of the architecture.</p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><strong>The private key stays on the hardware token</strong> — ZenRIS neither sees it nor copies it.</li>
        <li><strong>The PIN is strictly local</strong>, on the token's station, even if the request came from another desk.</li>
        <li><strong>Non-exportable station identity</strong>, with a cryptographic browser–station binding.</li>
        <li><strong>Certificate bound to operator–tax ID–contract</strong>, with a full audit of every operation.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap za-payoff">
      <p class="pull-quote">One token. One station.<br /><b>The whole clinic reports.</b></p>
      <div class="grid grid-3 za-before-after">
        <article class="card bad">
          <span class="ba-tag">Without ZenAgent</span>
          <p>You carry the token from the front desk to the physician to accounting. You install SIUI on every
            computer. You keep track of "which machine has the certificate today".</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card good">
          <span class="ba-tag ok">With ZenAgent</span>
          <p>The token sits on one station, connected once. Any computer reports from the browser. Routing is
            automatic, the PIN stays local, everything is audited.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card soon">
          <span class="ba-tag pending">On the roadmap</span>
          <p>The same agent architecture extends to fiscal devices (cash registers) — through a dedicated adapter,
            verified on a real device. Clearly marked as roadmap, not a feature of today.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section za-cta">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>CNAS claims become a non-event.</h2>
      <p class="lead">Bring your token, your contract and your compliance questions to the demo. We'll show you how a
        single ZenAgent station covers the whole clinic — and how everything stays audited, fail-closed and with the
        keys on hardware.</p>
      <div class="za-ctas">
        <a class="btn btn-solid" href="/en/demo/">Book a demo</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/en/platforma/">See the whole platform →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
